metadata.name: FXHASH Generative Logo #378
metadata.description:
Unique iteration of the first Generative Token minted on fxhash.

It also servers as the actual logo of the platform. It represents the generative processes driving fxhash tokens. Generative Tokens are fed with a unique hash to produce unique outputs based on the hash — they are functions with a hash as single input.

The growth that comes out of the text is driven by a "Dividing-Aggregating Walkers" (DAW) algorithm. The hash drives all the DAW settings, as well as a mutation factor which is responsible for changes in each Walker parameters as they divide.

Some iterations will produce very simple outputs whereas others might be more chaotic.

Piece by @ciphrd for fxhash

metadata.name: Cradle #62
metadata.description:
Billions of years old, ancient remains decay across our Solar System. Mere transient visitors to our star, their ephemeral presence on our worlds is embodied in their creations. In the shadow of their megalithic constructions, we wonder what they might have brought to us.

They brought life.

----

Live mode controls:
'r' - change resolution
's' - save PNG
'f' - render at full speed
'space' - stop/continue rendering

The image quality gradually improves over time. The rendering speed is reduced by default - press 'f' for the maximum speed.

Rendering may be GPU intensive.

The more they flip. The more you’ll make.

p5.js –> Blockchain

Artist note:

Primary royalties are split 95-5% between artist and The Processing Foundation.

Secondary royalties go to the minters (99.9% of the 15%).

The preview thumbnails don’t do justice to the artworks. Please run the code to appreciate them better. Also, remember to check the alternate higher resolution renders using [a].

Some preview thumbnails might look slightly different to the artwork seen when running the code. This is due to the resolution difference between the capture module and the live code on your device. 

Please get in touch in the event of a blank preview thumbnail.

metadata.name: Shapes on a Plane #450
metadata.description:
“Shapes on a Plane” explores imaginary structures and worlds through simple shapes. It’s intended for small-scale print.

As a kid I was obsessed with Lego, Duplo, wooden building blocks... anything I could make something with.

I’d spend hours building things, imagining new worlds, new machines, new concepts, then i’d take them apart and create a whole new idea to explore.

To me, this piece to me is a reminder of that time - many days spent exploring ideas with those simple objects - no care for viability, for marketability, for audiences or business. Just pure fun.

Without this time in my life, I doubt I’d have found my passion for creating in the way I do today.

metadata.name: 𝐃𝐞𝐚𝐫𝐭𝐡 #66
metadata.description:
Witness hundreds of small geometric objects gather under one roof to create a cosmic rain!

Ever since I was a child, I have always been good with geometric objects. I used to draw objects such as cubes, cylinders and prisms on paper for hours. As if I'm getting lost in every line between those geometric objects! In this way, every detail of geometry in my daily life and in my other existing life attracts my attention.

Recently, I have been doing research on colors and color palettes, it is really impressive how thousands of color mixtures affect each other and the psychology of living things!

∽∽depending on the screen size you can get different resolutions, which brings out a different side of the project! so you can run this project on all screen sizes and get the output!∽∽

Key:
- Press "s" to export an PNG image


Made with p5.js

metadata.name: Elementary Cellular Emoji Automata #761
metadata.description:
Features the full set of 1761 emojis, including skin tone and gender modifiers and all flags.
Arranged using the full 256 ruleset of one-dimensional cellular automata

If “random seed” is true then the seed of the generation is randomized using Math.random() meaning that the pattern will change on regeneration.
The ruleset, emoji, colors and all other properties will remain the same.

Auto-adjusts to screen size

Compatible with as many browsers and systems as possible

metadata.name: Digital Surface 1 #114
metadata.description:
The mechanics of Digital Surface is inspired by nature and the aesthetics by pixels. Digital Surface is an attempt to find an autonomous visual logic for a digital world made by machines.
The image is created one pixel after another, calculating the proceeding pixel based on the previous generations.
The color palettes are influenced by colors occurring in nature mixed with artificial man made colors that we see more today, aiming to look for new combinations that are pleasant to humans and natively digital.

Render time can be long. Once the image is completed, press "s" to save in a small size, "m" in a medium, "l" in a large, "x" in a xlarge and "w" to save with the size of the window.

Digital Surface is a 5 series project. Each Series is released singularly, the first being Digital Surface 1. The main differentiation for series 1 is that each image contains 2 colors.
This is Francesco Forcellini Studio's first NFT project broadening their field of work from physical to digital.

Built using p5js, published under CC-BY-NC-4.0 license.

Once the collection will be fully minted, the variations button will be disabled.

metadata.name: SC.002 : Studies Series #211
metadata.description:
This hybrid project combines elements of 2 previous drops: Glomularus + Inertial Packing. The project is intended as a giveaway to show appreciation to the community of collectors who previously have minted my work.

SC.002 includes multiple constraint systems, based on Verlet and Euler Integration approaches, with attached geometric primitives and softbody Prototubes. Numerous user controls are included:

Interaction:

Mouse/Trackpad:
drag -> camera rotation
drag + CMD/CTR -> camera pan
scroll wheel/pinch -> camera zoom

Key Input:
-, +: reduce | increase Node Count
{, }: reduce | increase Packing Dimension
c, v: reduce | increase Node Adhesion
h, j: reduce | increase Node Jitter
b, n: disable| enable Node-Node Collision
z, x: reduce | increase Stick Constraint
a, s: hide | show Nodes
q, w: hide | show Wireframe
d, f: reduce | increase Prototube Thickness
p: screen capture

Tip:
1. There are 8 unique geometries, should you be inclined to collect a full set.
2. Bringing values outside of "rational" range is encouraged.

Note:
Please post your favorite SC.002 screen captures
TW: @iragreenberg
IG: @greenberg.ira

Built with Three.js, PByte.js, TypeScript, Node

metadata.name: geometric tiles #43
metadata.description:
Hello everyone, this is my first fxhash project.

There are three types of mints you can get: checkers, stairs and rectangular prisms - there is equal chance of getting any of those. 

There is also 8% chance of getting the rarity mint which is the mint with the grainy effect over it. However, you should check my twitter out in order to see the preview of all the mint types you can get.

The inspiration behind this project was M.C. Escher.
